ic arterioles"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EChylomicrons are large lipoprotein particles that transport dietary lipids from the intestines to other tissues in the body. Due to their large size, they cannot enter blood vessels directly. Instead, they are absorbed into \u003Cstrong\u003Elymphatic capillaries\u003C/strong\u003E (lacteals) within the intestinal villi.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPortal veins\u003C/strong\u003E carry nutrients from the digestive tract to the liver but do not directly absorb chylomicrons. \u003Cstrong\u003ESystemic arteries\u003C/strong\u003E carry oxygenated blood away from the heart and are not involved in absorption. \u003Cstrong\u003EBlood capillaries\u003C/strong\u003E are too small to accommodate chylomicrons. \u003Cstrong\u003EMesenteric arterioles\u003C/strong\u003E supply blood to the intestines but do not absorb nutrients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFrom the lymphatic capillaries, chylomicrons travel through progressively larger lymphatic vessels before entering the bloodstream via the thoracic duct, which empties into the left subclavian vein.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Chylomicrons are absorbed into lymphatic capillaries (lacteals) in intestinal villi due to their large size.","The lymphatic system transports dietary fats from the intestine to the bloodstream via the thoracic duct.","Chylomicrons cannot enter blood capillaries directly due to their size."],"references":["Hall JE. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2021. Chaper 66; pg. 831.","Bender DA, Cunningham SM. Introduction to nutrition and metabolism. CRC Press; 2021.","Salway JG. Metabolism at a Glance. John Wiley \u0026 Sons; 2016.","Chandel NS. Lipid Metabolism. Cold Spring Harb Perspect Biol. 2021 Sep 1;13(9):a040576. doi: 10.1101/cshperspect.a040576. PMID: 34470787; PMCID: PMC8411952.","Wakil SJ, Abu-Elheiga LA. Fatty 